            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="stopnitskyU" start="957.987" end="x">. . . it was always dark, it was dark in general, there was no more light, one couldn't have any, so people would get out and who had luck managed to come back. The one who had no luck [could not manage to return] was shot. Because during the whole evening the <a class="placename" href="#vothC150" type="camp">ghetto</a> was surrounded. And with special searchlights—as soon as they would hear a shot—they would turn their light at that point and would begin to shoot at that point. In this way many people were killed but every day regularly they would send away a transport two thousand Jews to <a class="placename" href="#vothC4" type="camp">Auschwitz</a>. That was definitely known. In the meantime while I was in hiding with my family . . .</span>
        </li>
